{
  "doc_id": "9666",
  "text": "Reliance on a single drug to treat 'continents' of people afflicted with schistosomiasis encourages the search for new drugs and drug targets [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . RNAi has proven to be a key research tool in this endeavor by identifying gene products that are essential to parasite survival (e.g., [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] ). In this report, we demonstrate that RNAi of the single gene schistosome ortholog of huPLK1 leads to degenerative changes in the morphology of S. mansoni somules. Our findings are consistent with those very recently reported by Bickle and colleagues [CITATION_9] as are our previous unsuccessful attempts to discern phenotypes consequent on RNAi of SmPLK1 in adult schistosomes [CITATION_10] . Because somules undergo major transformative changes as they adapt to the mammalian host, it's possible that they are more sensitive to perturbations in gene expression than adults. With the knowledge that SmPLK1 contributes to survival and that huPLK1 is a well-validated drug target for treatment of various cancers [CITATION_11] [CITATION_12] [CITATION_13] , we obtained pre-clinically and clinically advanced small molecule inhibitors of huPLK1 that might form starting points for the development of novel anti-schistosomals.",
